A US Marshal is a federal law enforcement officer responsible for serving and executing various judicial processes and orders related to the federal court system. They are appointed by the President of the United States and serve a terms of four years or until retirement. Their main roles and responsibilities include:
-Serving and executing federal criminal and civil process, such as arrest warrants, subpoenas, and court orders;
-Protecting witnesses, judicial officials, and high-profile individuals;
-Assisting in the apprehension and transport of federal prisoners;
-Enforcing orders of the Prevention of Domestic Violence and Protection of Children;
-Conducting investigations related to the jurisdiction of the US Marshal Service;
-Assisting in the execution of search and arrest warrants; and
-Training and coordinating local, state and international agencies and teams during investigations and apprehensions.

The main differences between a US Marshal and a police officer or an FBI agent are the jurisdiction and the specific roles and responsibilities of each position:
-Police officers work for local or state law enforcement agencies and have jurisdiction over crimes and incidents within their local or state boundaries;
-FBI agents work for the Federal Bureau of Investigation and deal mainly with investigating and preventing federal crimes; while US Marshals deal mainly with the execution of judicial processes and orders related to the federal court system and the protection of high-profile individuals and witnesses involved in federal cases. US Marshals often collaborate and work closely with local, state and FBI agencies for the execution of various investigations and apprehensions related to the jurisdiction of the US Marshal Service or the specific case at hand. US Marshals and FBI agents often share some similar roles and responsibilities during these collaborations, but the main focus of each position remains different.
